When updating the issue type via Rest API, the differences between workflows is ignored.

Given 2 issue types with the following workflow statuses:
 * Bug (workflow: open -> closed)
 * Improvement (workflow: feedback -> resolve)

When updating the issue type from Bug to Improvement via the Web UI, it is not possible to update the issue type directly if the target issue type workflow does not have a matching status. You have to go through the "Move Issue" flow and select a new valid status in the workflow that applies to the target issue type.

However, the same does not apply for the Rest API, where you can update the issue type directly (without having to go through the corresponding "move issue" API)

Example: a HTTP POST request to [/rest/api/2/issue/\{issueKey}|https://cd.bb.atl-test.space/jira/testing/rest/api/2/issue/17621] with the following body:
{code:java}
{
  "fields": {
    "issuetype": { 
      "id": $new_issue_type_id
    }
  }
}
{code}
*Expected result:*
 * Operation fails with an error

*Actual result:*
 * Operation succeeds with 204. Checking the issue through the Web UI shows the new issue type with the old workflow status (which is invalid in the new workflow).

h3. *Problem Definition*

The JIRA is recently updated to use the round avatar but there are customers that prefer the square avatar. 

h3. *Suggested Solution*

Add an option for the customer to choose round or square according to their preference. It will be even better if this can be done on user-basis instead of the entire instance. 

h3. *Why this is important*
 
Some avatar or logo are designed in a square so the rounded avatar caused it to not being displayed fully. 

h3. *Workaround*

As a workaround, you can add the following to your Announcement Banner at *Administration > System > Announcement banner (under User Interface)*. 
{code:html}
<style>
.aui-avatar-inner {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-content: center;
    border-radius: 100%;
    overflow: visible;
}
</style>
{code}

h3. Problem Definition

When text fields which use Wiki style renderer are updated, the activities are shown in Activity Stream.

If "h1" heading is used in the update, it is rendered differently in Activity Stream compared with the one in the issue page. The heading is alined in the center.

 !image-2018-11-28-10-41-32-465.png|thumbnail! 

When we check it on the developer console, the style seems to be specified as follows.

{code:css}
.gadget h1 {
    text-align: center;
}
{code}

This behavior can be seen regardless of the dashboard layout.
Also, the other headings like "h2", "h3" are working as expected.

h3. Suggested Solution

It would be nicer if "h1" heading is rendered as the other ones are.

h3. Issue summary
Changing the color configuration in the Look and Feel functionality does not affect the Quick search styling.

h3. Steps to reproduce
 # Go to Administration > System > Look and Feel
 # Modify the color scheme for _Menu Item Highlight Background Color_ or any other relevant configuration.
 # Refresh the page and go to the system dashboard.

h3. Expected results
The selected color should change the link colors everywhere in JIRA.

h3. Actual results
The link colors do not affect the items in the Quick search menu.
 !screenshot-1.png|thumbnail!  !screenshot-2.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Workaround
Apply this on the announcement banner, replacing the colors/color codes in it to be what you require :
{code}
</style>
<style type="text/css">
.icon-container.icon-container.quick-search-view-all
{
color:black !important;
}

a.icon-container.icon-container.quick-search-view-all.quick-search-active
{
color:white !important;
}

a.icon-container.icon-container:hover
{
background-color:#990033 !important;
}

.icon-container.icon-container.quick-search-active
{ 
   background-color:#990033 !important;
}
</style>
{code}
* Full credit to [~it1344275202] for this workaround.

h3. Problem Definition.
If we run an Indexing especially Background Reindex, while it will be executed in one node, the information will be shown in the other nodes as well. In case that there is a problem with the Re-indexing and it is stuck, there is no way we can know which node is doing the Indexing from the UI. Then, if canceling is not doing anything as well, the only way to stop it is to stop the node but since there is no information on which node that is doing it, we won't know which node that needs to be stopped. While we can check this in the logs or database, it is not an easy task to do.

h3. Suggested Solution.
To have the Reindexing page to show which node is doing the background reindexing to help the Admin and Support on the investigation in case there is an issue with the Reindexing process.

h3. Notes
To get the information from the database, we can use the query below with a caveat:
{code:sql}
select * from clustermessage where message like '%reindexAll%';
{code}
(!) The message will only appear if the Reindexing is already finished
{code:sql}select * from replicatedindexoperation where operation like '%REINDEX%';{code}
(!) There is a cleaner job for this table hence if the row is old enough, it will be removed
{code:sql}select * from clusterlockstatus where lock_name like '%DefaultReindexMessageManager.messageLock%';{code}

When adding option 37 to a custom field, this cannot be moved up anymore. Seems JavaScript is a bit messed and sends the wrong requests for those selected values.

This is the URL that the move up button needs to execute:

{code}
<a id="moveUp_26381" href="EditCustomFieldOptions!moveUp.jspa?fieldConfigId=23836&amp;atl_token=B8YO-FLDM-36UO-7500%7Cfdc8e04fb13689033b7f2567bf2bdee7ed85fc4d%7Clin&amp;selectedValue=26381"><img src="/jira733/images/icons/arrow_up_blue.gif" title="Move this option up" width="16" height="16" border="0"></a>
{code}

Notice the Selected Value on that.

When executing the request, JavaScript for some reason sends a different request, that requests it to move to position 37. 

{code}
http://10.125.88.87:8080/jira733/secure/admin/EditCustomFieldOptions!moveUp.jspa?fieldConfigId=23836&atl_token=B8YO-FLDM-36UO-7500%7Cfdc8e04fb13689033b7f2567bf2bdee7ed85fc4d%7Clin&selectedValue=26372
{code}

We can here see when option 36 executes the request, it requests the same selected value.

{code}
http://10.125.88.87:8080/jira733/secure/admin/EditCustomFieldOptions!moveUp.jspa?fieldConfigId=23836&atl_token=B8YO-FLDM-36UO-7500%7Cfdc8e04fb13689033b7f2567bf2bdee7ed85fc4d%7Clin&selectedValue=26372
{code}

There's currently no workaround to tackle this other than modifying the JavaScript calls to change the requests.

h3. Summary

{{AG.getAbsoluteURL()}} method in atlassian-gadgets-publisher-plugin returns URL with duplicate context paths in some specific circumstance.

h3. Environment

* atlassian-gadgets-publisher-plugin-4.2.31.jar
* Base URL is set as the following format
*- http(s)://*xxx*.yyy.zzz/*xxx*
*- http(s)://*aaa*.bbb.ccc.ddd/*aaa*

h3. Steps to Reproduce

Please copy the following minimum code and paste it to your browser's developer console.

{code:javascript}
jQuery = {};
jQuery.ajaxSettings = {};
AJS = {};
AG = {};

jQuery.ajaxSettings.baseUrl = "https://xxx.yyy.zzz/xxx";
AJS.contextPath = function() { return "/xxx"; }

AG.isRelativeURL = function (url) {
    return !/^(http|https):\/\//.test(url);
};

AG.getAbsoluteURL = function (url) {
    // this currently needs to be set in every gadget. We should be injecting this via publisher.
    if (AG.isRelativeURL(url)) {
        var baseUrl =  jQuery.ajaxSettings.baseUrl || "";
        var contextPath = AJS.contextPath() || "";

        if (baseUrl && contextPath && startsWith(url, contextPath) && endsWith(baseUrl, contextPath)
        ) {
            baseUrl = baseUrl.substring(0, baseUrl.length - contextPath.length);
        }

        return baseUrl + url;
    } else {
        return url;
    }
};


function startsWith(str, prefix) {
    str = str || "";
    prefix = prefix || "";

    if (prefix === "") {
        return true;
    }
    return str.indexOf(prefix) === 0;

}

function endsWith(str, postfix) {
    str = str || "";
    postfix = postfix || "";

    if (postfix === "") {
        return true;
    }
    var indexOf = str.indexOf(postfix);
    return indexOf !== -1 && str.length - postfix.length === indexOf;
}
console.log(AG.getAbsoluteURL("/xxx/rest/api/"));
{code}

h3. Expected Results

The test code should return "https://xxx.yyy.zzz/xxx".

h3. Actual Results

The test code returned "https://xxx.yyy.zzz/xxx/xxx".
 
h3. Notes

This problem occurred because of the behavior of {{endsWith()}} method.
It seems to try to match the context path from *the beginning* of the base URL.

{code:javascript}
function endsWith(str, postfix) {
    ...
    var indexOf = str.indexOf(postfix);
    ...
}
{code}

h3. Problem Definition
In the KB [How to restrict project access to different isolated user groups | https://confluence.atlassian.com/jirakb/how-to-restrict-project-access-to-different-isolated-user-groups-290750862.html]  Is listed in the [Jira Server KB Space | https://confluence.atlassian.com/jirakb/jira-knowledge-base-781397172.html] and Notes:
{code}
This Knowledge Base article was written specifically for the Atlassian Server platform. Due to the Functional differences in Atlassian Cloud, the contents of this article cannot be applied to Atlassian Cloud applications.
{code}

However the KB does included Steps for both Jira Server and Jira Cloud, BUT the current Steps listed for Jira Cloud are not up to date with the current Cloud ADG3 Layout, as an EXE one section reads:
{quote}
granting the groups access to your instance at (Image of the Admin Settings Cog wheel that no longer exists in cloud) > User management > Application access and clicking the View configuration button for JIRA Cloud users.
{quote}

But the Actual Path for Jira Cloud currently is:
{quote}
(Image Icon for the new AppSwitcher the 9 square boxes in the lower left) >> Site Administration >> SITE SETTINGS >> Product Access
{quote}

h3. Suggested Solution
The Cloud Specific Steps should be removed from the Server KB and secondary KB for Cloud Specific configuration Added to the [Jira Cloud KB space | https://confluence.atlassian.com/jirakb/jira-knowledge-base-781397172.html], then add links between the two platform specific articles for easy transition between the Articles and better visibility.
 
h3. Workaround
Currently the Article Does Indicate the correct steps for permission changes and the actions to take for a Cloud Instance but the navigation paths to the menus are incorrect use "G+G" or "." to open up the search navigation to locate the desired menu location to make the noted change
